[[File:Roman artificial leg of bronze. Wellcome M0012307.jpg|thumb|The Capua leg (replica)]]

The '''Capua leg''' is an [[artificial leg]], found in a grave in [[Capua|Capua, Italy]]. Dating from 300 BC, the leg is one of the earliest known [[artificial limb|prosthetic limbs]]. The limb was kept at the [[Royal College of Surgeons of England|Royal College of Surgeons]] in London, but was destroyed in [[World War II]] during an air raid.<ref name="Cairo_Toe">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/6918687.stm "Cairo toe earliest fake body bit"], BBC News, 27 July 2007. Retrieved 27 July 2007.</ref> A copy of the limb is held at the [[Science Museum, London]].<ref>[http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/objects/classical_and_medieval_medicine/A646752.aspx "Roman artificial leg, c. 300 BC"], Science Museum (inventory #A646752).</ref>

